title: For Sale:  .17 HMR Stainless Steel Ruger 77/17 - Nearly new, only 250 shots
postcontent:
I am the original owner, having purchased this awesome rifle earlier this year. I paid $950 for it, and it's the Stainless Ruger 77/17. As some of you may know, Ruger ships their "stainless" rifles not as true stainless steel, but in their "Target Grey" finish. It's a matte coating, and as one who wanted a true stainless rifle, I talked with a gunsmith about changing the finish, then personally hand-polished the Target Grey away to reveal the beautiful stainless steel underneath. Gets me a lot of compliments at the range, as it's a unique rifle. 

I have carefully broken-in the barrel, and have fired only 250 shots (5 boxes) through it. It has the heavy barrel, laminated stock, and a target crowned muzzle (view-able in the pictures). I'm also including the original box, a soft Ruger case, two sets of scope rings (30mm intermediate rings, plus 1 inch standard rings), plus a box of ammo. I'm also including two Tipton one-piece carbon fiber cleaning rods (bought one at the small length and needed the larger one, so now I have two), plus patch holder and brush (I really never use brushes but it's yours if you want it). 

It's only 6 months old, and I'm selling it because I upgraded to a .223 Browning X-bolt, and my fiancee only wants me to keep one of them. Want it to go to a good home. Having paid $950 for it and carefully breaking it in, I'd like to get $650 for it. I will listen to strong offers outside of $650, but serious inquiries only.

title: For Sale/Trade:  LEE ENFIELD No. 4 MK. 1, .303 British
postcontent: 1944 No. 4 MK. 1 Lee Enfield up for sale. .303 British. Rifle is in great shape, especially considering it is 70+ years old. Numerous markings and proof marks, serial #'s appear to match. Believe it is a BSA. Wood and metal have aged well and have nice patina. Bolt action is smooth, shoots well, iron sights are surprisingly accurate, functioning safety. Passed gunsmith safety check. title: For Sale:  Arisaka Type 38 SUPERB! Full Mum/No Import/A+ Bore Series 26 The Best
postcontent: This is likely the finest condition Type 38 listed.and if some new ones showed up, its at least in the top 3 of all. A pristine mirror bore and wood and metal that says that this rifle somehow avoided the war. It has a full and deep impressed MUM and no import marks along with the cleaning rod and dust cover. It is not all numbers matching as the bolt is different, but the rest looks like it was put away soon after being made. Be sure to ask for all 25 photos I will send as there is NO WAY to describe this without at least 20 good pics. It has the ears on the front site, so not the earliest type and to be honest, I am not very knowledgeable about these models as I have owned all Type 99s until now. The rifle is not perfect like unissued, not like that, but it definitely did not see any active service and the few flaws are very minor. There are some small areas where the metal is not smooth but it is like very small and isolated spots of some type of pitting. Not rust and not corrosion, just that the metal is not glossy smooth. It looks like a defect in the steel casting surface more than corrosion. It is only some tiny areas behind the rear site that are under a square inch total. The rear site is a 2400 meter ladder and the bluing on the barrel is just as nice or nicer than the receiver. The wood is superb as well with none of the usual Arisaka roughness from use and war. Smooth surface with minor dings mostly near the buttplate as the handguard is like new. It is matching wood to the rest so it was not added later and the stock is almost the same with little to no handling marks. Just a few marks that look like they are from storage with the great majority of the wood same as new with just age..no dings or marks at all. Even the buttplate is among the finest I have seen. The markings under the MUM are TYPE 38 and it is a series 26 (before the serial number) which makes this a late 1930s production and thus the Kokura Arsenal formerly Tokyo (changed in 1936). These were the last series from this arsenal. Overall, other than some age related markings there is no real visible wear to the exterior. The wood at the very front where it meets the nosecap has a .25 inch chip but from the aging and coloration, I would seriously think this dates back to the 1930s as well. The metal parts on the bottom that are almost always patina or heavily worn and corroded are a nice dark original color and original finish. As the bore is so nice, it must have been fired very little as well. Ships ground for $32 and packed properly. If you are in the Southeast and it is significantly less, I will lower it to match. Paypal OK if discrete and must add 3% (sorry, not for me) If you like the finest examples for your collection but dont want to pay museum prices, this is for you. Not like the typical Arisakas at all, this is something special you do not see often.

title: For Sale:  "David Tubbs" Chrome Silicone Steel Spring Kit for AR-15 Rifles. & .45 JHP ammo.
postcontent:
I have for sale a Chrome Silicone Steel (For AR-15/M-16 will work for any length from Carbine to Rifle and anything in between).  It is a David Tubbs brand kit. Designed by the world class shooter himself and by far the best quality and reliability upgrades you can do for the platform.  
The kit includes:
(1) Extractor Spring
(1) Ejector Spring
(1) Hammer Spring
(1) Trigger Spring
(1) Buffer Spring (Flat Wound Spring)
(2) 30rd Magazine Springs (also Flat Wound springs) ie. The best design. 

Traditional or Factory springs that come in all AR's come with cheap quality (music wire) spring steel springs. There were many problems with the extractor springs breaking and causing the entire system to STOP WORKING AND JAM!  So there have been the little rubber "Spring Buffers" that have tried to remedy the problem by claiming even if the spring breaks the buffer will give enough buffer action from the elasticity of the rubber/plastic to keep it cycling, but this is hardly ever true.  In fact all of the springs are only supposed to be used for 2,000 to 2,500 rounds before they are supposed to be changed out! Obviously they often last longer than that in many cases but statistically one of them fail around 2,000 rds. usually it is the extractor or the buffer springs but any of them fail and the system fails completely. So David Tubbs found that using Chrome Silicone Steel is far superior in every way possible and usually surpases 25,000 rounds before failure!  And they are smoother in their travel, lending to smoother function. If you don't believe me do your homework, I did. And it was the best kit I found. The only reason I am selling this kit is it was my spare kit for my AR which I sold. So this kit is brand new and still in the plastic packaging! Never used or even installed. If you were going to do only one upgrade to your AR or M-16 this kit is definitely what I would do. Especially for the cost, there is nothing you can do that will benifit your rifle more than good springs. After all that is what causes the system to function. If you worry about your friend or family member serving in the military this kit is what I would buy and send them as fast as I could. The military is known for being cheap and trying to squeeze every last cent out of everything they buy. Personally I wouldn't want to wait for the springs in my defense rifle to fail, possibly in the middle of a battle before I changed them out. Ask any serviceman that's been in a firefight if they would want to change out any springs while bullets are flying. I can guarantee you the answer is a big NO. I would hope you would do your own research and check out David tubbs on YouTube or his website and you will quickly learn that this guy is very intelligent and knows springs, especially high quality firearm springs.
Email me a reply if you're interested, I paid $80 which included shipping for this set and I have this set for $50.  If you want to see pictures of my springs you can go to my ad on: 
 http://portland.wweek.com/SportsEquipForSale/50-ar-15-david-tubbs-high-performance-spring-kit/13056361
Thanks for looking. PS- I also have 40rds. or Black Ops Hollow Point Ammunition in .45acp for sale as well, New in the boxes. I paid $32 per box of 20rds. I'll sell them all for $30

title: For Sale:  1874  Long Colt 45  Cavalry Ainsworth SAA, Model Single Action

All Original , Excellent Condition with a lot of Original Blue , Crisp all Matching Numbers , 7 1/2 inch barrel, Has All the Correct Inspection and Proof marking ,The OWA Colt refer to the earliest issued Single Action Army Guns which were inspected by Orville W. Ainsworth . Ainsworth was the Ordnance sub-inspector at the Colt Factory for the first 13 Months (oct.,1873 to Nov.,1874 ) of the Single Action Army production .It was Ainsworth who inspected the Colts used by Col. George A . Custer`s 7th Cavalry at the Battle of the Little Bighorn . The number range of possible Little Bighorn Colts is 4500-7527 . Ainsworth inspected through serial number 14998. In 1893 the .45 U S Colt SAA revolvers were retired by the Cavalry . In 1895-96 the Government returned 2000 SAA revolvers to Colt to be refurbished ,1200 had the barrels altered to 5 1/2 inches long and in 1998 14,900 of the SAA revolvers were altered the same way (5 1/2 in. barrels ) at the Springfield Armory.
